{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502867"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:51:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:51:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1907"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1907"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.01,0.09,0.63,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109584"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1907"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91966"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"6147"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12374"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38107"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109584"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a painful, swollen right knee. The previous day he injured his knee while playing soccer, pivoting and experiencing a sensation of the knee giving way. He fell but was able to get up and hobble off the field. Over the next few hours, he noticed swelling around the knee. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The right knee is swollen and the bulge sign is positive, with no clear bony deformity. There is tenderness along the medial joint line. He is unable to fully extend the knee. There is no laxity on anterior or posterior movement of the tibia against the femur.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medial collateral ligament tear","Lateral meniscal tear","Anterior cruciate ligament tear","Medial meniscal tear","Patella fracture"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a classic presentation of a \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial meniscal tear\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly a bucket handle tear, which can cause a mechanical block to extension (locked knee) after a twisting injury. The combination of joint line tenderness, inability to fully extend the knee, and a history of pivoting injury are highly suggestive. Recognising these features is important for junior doctors, as prompt orthopaedic referral is required to prevent long-term joint damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial collateral ligament tear\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with medial knee pain and tenderness, but does not usually cause locking or inability to extend the knee. There is often instability to valgus stress, which is not described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral meniscal tear\u003C/strong\u003E can also cause joint line tenderness and mechanical symptoms, but the location of tenderness in this case is medial, and the mechanism of injury more commonly affects the medial meniscus due to its relative immobility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior cruciate ligament tear\u003C/strong\u003E often results from a similar non-contact pivoting injury and may present with a popping sensation and rapid swelling due to haemarthrosis. However, it is usually associated with instability (positive anterior drawer or Lachman test) rather than a locked knee, and there is no mention of laxity here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatella fracture\u003C/strong\u003E would present with anterior knee pain, swelling, and often an inability to perform a straight leg raise, but would be associated with bony tenderness and possibly deformity, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the distinguishing features of meniscal versus ligamentous or bony injuries is essential for early diagnosis, appropriate imaging, and timely referral, which can significantly impact long-term knee function and patient outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A medial meniscal tear can present with a locked knee and inability to fully extend after a twisting injury.","Joint line tenderness and mechanical symptoms such as locking or giving way are key features of meniscal injury.","Distinguishing between ligamentous and meniscal injuries is essential for appropriate acute management and referral."],"references":["Carek SM. Hip and Knee Injuries. Prim Care 2020;47:115-31. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32014129/","Raj MA, Bubnis MA. Knee Meniscal Tears. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK431067/","Lento PH, Akuthota V. Meniscal injuries: A critical review. J Back Musculoskelet Rehabil. 2000 Jan 1;15(2):55-62. doi: 10.3233/bmr-2000-152-302. PMID: 22388443. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22388443/","Bhan K. Meniscal Tears: Current Understanding, Diagnosis, and Management. Cureus. 2020 Jun 13;12(6):e8590. doi: 10.7759/cureus.8590. PMID: 32676231; PMCID: PMC7359983. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32676231/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91966"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1907"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91966"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-23T09:32:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-23T09:32:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1907"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109584"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":nul